A civil society organisation under the aegis of Centre for Policy Advocacy and Leadership Development, a member of a coalition of civil society groups that recently called for the resignation of deputy senate president, Ovie Omo-Agege from his position in the senate, has described the action as baseless and the allegation, mendacious, and therefore withdraws from being part of the call. Recall that a group, Coalition of Civil Society and Youth Groups in Nigeria, in collaboration with other organisations led by Comrade Solomon Adodo, had last week called on Omo-Agege to resign from his position as Deputy Senate President and also vacate his seat as senator representing Delta Central Senatorial District, or face a suit in the law court and mobilisation of Nigerian youths against him. Adodo’s coalition had alleged that Omo-Agege was convicted in the United States of America, USA, an allegation the Deputy Senate President, in a statement signed by his Special Adviser on Media and Publicity, Yemi Odenuga, immediately debunked.